<review>Awesomeness
Westchester Skate Plaza is a Fam Fav< /review><pics>None</pics><resp>None</resp><gmap_id>0x80c2b0ea03911d01:0x6298cc044ff37bb8<//gmap_id></record>

<name>Gary Tarbell<//name><pics>None< /pics><user_id>114405722015261208032< /user_id><date>1536470019007< /date><text>I don't know where to start.  I'm not a street skaters, so I won't go on a long rant about the complete lack of transitions.  If the locals like the design, that's NOMB.  But it does bug me how the local skaters are discriminated against.

This park is listed as open until 10pm.  The signs in the park say 10:30pm.

And yet, at 9:30pm on a Saturday, there are no lights running in the skate park.  The  locals continue to skate through 10 p.m. without lights just getting by on the incidental light from the tennis courts next door.

The really frustrating thing is that there are 8 tennis courts with lights shining as bright as the sun at 10 p.m. even though the tennis court sign says they close at 9 p.m.

The tennis courts are completely empty.  So the city would rather waste hours and hours of electricity on tennis courts that are not even being used.  But the half dozen skaters in the plaza are not even accommodated to the time listed on the sign.

Now, of course there are cameras watching them from both sides of the skatepark.  But providing light would cost too much?

If this park wants to close at 9pm, then they should do it officially and alter all the signs.  But they should be consistent and turn out the lights for the tennis courts and the empty soccer field.

This is the same story I see in cities all over the country.  Cities love to pat themselves on the backs during the ribbon cutting ceremonies for these skateparks.  But actually supporting skateboarders is just too much effort for them.<//text>< resp>
None</resp>

<userid>113184154887512533094</userid>< Name>
Scott Carni< /Name>
<date>1518586156265<//date><Rate>5<//Rate>< text>
Open in July of 2010 the skate park was designed in part by Steve Berra of The Berrics. Partial funding came from the Annenberg Foundation and the LA Parks Foundation.
This is an urban skatepark with plenty of rails, staircases, jumps, Etc. Many days during the month you'll find professionals practicing and honing their skills at this park. Skaters come from all over the world to participate. The park averages roughly 250 people per day of all ages and backgrounds. It is attached to Westchester Recreation Center and is situated near the playground and gymnasiums. Located at 7000 Manchester Avenue. The recreation center has video security cameras throughout the facility. Helmets are not required but highly recommended< /text>

<Review>Education-wise, you get out what you put in. I got my Master's in Education there, and am happy with how I could be a full-time student while also holding a full-time job. I'm happy that the instructors were there for me if I needed something, and fairly accommodating. Don't expect to feel like you're attending a brick and mortar campus--- you're not. Think of it as a guided independent study. It takes a lot of self-discipline and want-to.

I see a lot of bad reviews based solely on Financial Aid issues, which I would caution anyone about basing their educational choices on-- their financial aid policies come from the Federal Government, just like any other school who is able to use Financial Aid. Just like the brick-and-mortar school I got my Bachelor's at. If there is a delay, I would bet it's usually because of a policy that is outside of the school's control. Any current student who has issues with financial aid should ask someone there to give them a step by step of what is happening with their finances.

Over all I'm happy with my educational experience with this school. They get a lot of crap for being for-profit, but for the student that might be a good thing. Think about it-- where do you get better customer service? The DMV or Starbucks? You had better believe it's the place that knows you can choose to go elsewhere.</Review>< pictures>

< review>
This university is perfect for those that are ready to use all of the tools available and get the work done.  It‚Äôs a horrible university for procrastinators and excuse makers.  The staff can only be as helpful as you allow them to be.  Staying in regular contact will ensure this.  The courses are challenging but not for the sake of making work tougher.  They are challenging because you actually learn something when the class is done.  I'm only 5 classes into my MBA and I have already been able to apply what I have learned to my job in finance.  Whatever one may feel they loose from not being in a lecture hall is made up for it in the through use of the textbooks and support materials.  I can access my work and reading material from computer, tablet and mobile phone.  Ashford U. even converts your text book to audio so you can "read" while driving.  All of these convenient resources eliminate most of the typical barriers that interfere with getting an education.   Once you're enrolled the only thing you‚Äôre left to contend with is your desire to do the work.< /review>

<Text>I loved my experience with this school. I almost didn't sign up because of bad reviews which is why I'm leaving this here. I've been enrolled at 2 brick and mortar schools and did not finish until Ashford. They accepted ALL of my credits, the classes are structured for your success, and you know exactly what is required from you. If you fail out of this school it is your own fault. It requires A LOT of work on your part. If you are a horrible writer you might want to brush up on your skills as the entire degree program requires writing. I've only ran into a couple instances where I needed help from the school. Every single time I needed something this school went out of their way to make sure my questions were answered and that what ever problem I had was taken care of. If you are not doing your work or run into financial issues with the government please don't leave a review because of something not in the schools control. We are adults so we are required to take care of ourselves. Its not the schools job to inform your instructor of your issues or to speak with the government to resolve your financial aid issues. Further, I've never had a problem with a class or assignment that the instructor wasn't willing to work with me on. This may be because I always did my work and always had it on time. If you are not giving effort who is going to want to help you? Nobody in life from school to work so if you run into an issue you should really examine the possibility that the issue occurred because of your own actions or inaction.<//Text>< pics>

<Text>I have read many of these reviews and wow, people are very wrong about this school! I have had NO problems whatsoever with the administration, financial aid, stipends, instructors, staff or accommodations. I think the people who are posting these extremely negative reviews about lack of financial aid, and problems with counselors and staff are leaving out the important details! I have found through investigation, that most people who do not receive the financial aid they say they were promised is because of the use of financial aid elsewhere, failed classes, and dropped courses, or changes in financial living conditions. Shame on those people for misleading others and giving Ashford University a bad name!

I have been attending Ashford University for over three years. I am in my Senior year, and I am working hard to graduate. I want to first say that the expectations for attending an online university are mixed, because I think that most people believe that earning a degree online will be easy and trust me, this is not the case. If you are contemplating earning an online degree, you MUST be self motivated, dedicated, and be able to manage your time effectively. Be prepared to read, read, read, research, research, research, write, write and write some more. You must have the ability to take constructive criticism and apply criticism to future work/assignments. You have to stay on top of your work because if you fall behind you will be overwhelmed. You must stay focused, and keep working, even through difficulties, and everyday life.

The instructors expect a level of dedication, maturity, and want to see you work hard, grades are not given, they are earned! The instructors are actively responsive to correspondence but do not expect an instructor to respond to you at 11PM, an hour before your 12 page final essay is due. This is where I stress, time management. Instructors get back to you fast but do not expect them to in a time crunch. Some do, but some will get back to you the next day. Of course, life gets in the way sometimes, you may fall ill, your children may be sick and you might need an extension, extensions are not handed out, and do not, for any reason expect them. Only request them when you truly need an extra day. All of my instructors have been sympathetic, and have allowed accommodations when needed but use them sparingly. We are all adults and we know that if something is due and it is not turned in on time, it is late and that is the bottom line. I have had some instructors who have been the reason for my motivation and desire to do better with each and every assignment. I have never had a problem with an instructor. I have however, had very strict instructors/professors, so each class is different. Just be prepared to work hard in every class and you will never be blindsided by expectations.  You get what you give, give your all and you will get the best grade you can for yourself, even if that grade is a C or a B!

The counselors have been amazing, they now have a new feature that allows you to talk to an alternate counselor if your counselor is not available. This means that your calls never go unanswered, ever!

This is college, not a day care, if college was easy everyone would do it. If you are not prepared to work hard and commit to a journey of ups and downs, then college is not for you. Ashford University is AMAZING! Yes, it costs more than a traditional college, but you are paying for the convenience that an online learning platform affords you. You are never alone, you have access to resources 24/7. If you choose to attend Ashford University, choose to go all the way, never give up and please, if you are going to share a review, tell the whole truth so that others are properly informed. Ashford Rocks!< /Text>< pics>

<Rating>5<//Rating><Text>I loved my experience with this school. I almost didn't sign up because of bad reviews which is why I'm leaving this here. I've been enrolled at 2 brick and mortar schools and did not finish until Ashford. They accepted ALL of my credits, the classes are structured for your success, and you know exactly what is required from you. If you fail out of this school it is your own fault. It requires A LOT of work on your part. If you are a horrible writer you might want to brush up on your skills as the entire degree program requires writing. I've only ran into a couple instances where I needed help from the school. Every single time I needed something this school went out of their way to make sure my questions were answered and that what ever problem I had was taken care of. If you are not doing your work or run into financial issues with the government please don't leave a review because of something not in the schools control. We are adults so we are required to take care of ourselves. Its not the schools job to inform your instructor of your issues or to speak with the government to resolve your financial aid issues. Further, I've never had a problem with a class or assignment that the instructor wasn't willing to work with me on. This may be because I always did my work and always had it on time. <Date>1432054193554</Date><Rating>5< /Rating>< review>
I have been an online Ashford Student for about 6 months now and I love this school. It is so easy to understand and flexible with my schedule. I am getting challenged in every class and the teachers are never hard to reach. They do an excellent job of providing guidance in the classroom as well as explaining deadlines and expectations of class participation and final research papers. My only qualm is the finance department is a mess. It took me about 4 months to complete all my information because I had spoken to- without exaggeration- 10 different people. In their attempts to make the financial aid process simpler, I think there is a lack of communication between campuses. However, I was never charged for things I was not aware of, the process just took much longer than an on campus university. Great school. Absolutely recommend it.< /review>

<GmapID>0x87e26390275bfabf:0xb3af0f00dfc636df< /GmapID>< text>
So far I have really enjoyed my time at Ashford. I have an associates already from a traditional university and am attending Ashford with about a year left to complete my BA in Psychology. I'm taking all upper level classes which are challenging but rewarding. I have found all of my professors to be clear, attentive and responsive when I need help or have a question. The financial aid department could stand a little improvement. It took FOREVER to get me my refund check but that's mostly because of stupid little things like the last line of my tax return transcript getting cut off when I uploaded it, ect. When I first started I was connected with a military student advisor, Nick Reed, who was very knowledgeable and attentive. Transferring all my credit from my two previous brick and mortar universities was a breeze they accepted all 83 credits I'd earned!< /text>

<rating>5</rating>< text>
Ashford University is an awesome school!  Perfect for military members and their dependents!  The quality of the textbooks are not too complex, and stay current with the modern world.  The counselors that I've had experience with are very friendly and helpful, and seem like they actually enjoy their work.  There is a variety of degrees to choose from, and I've learned a lot since I've attended!  The online environment is very flexible for military students, and there is military tuition assistance available, on top of the already low tuition costs!  The only negative that I can think of is the school switching my enrollment counselor without notice, but it wasn't that much of an inconvenience.  Ashford is the best that I've attended, and I would definitely recommend this school to anyone who is serious about personally satisfying his/her life!<//text>

<rate>5</rate>< Review>
Like most other things in life - no school is perfect for every type of student.  I had some professors that were awesome and others that would not give an inch - for any reason.  As a retired military veteran, I was one of the first military members in Ashford's military program.  When I started with Ashford, part of my job in the military was to research and vet schools that wanted to be approved to participate in the military's Tuition Assistance program.  Ashford scored very high in quality of education and cost.  I transferred from another school that I was not happy with at the time; due to their team assignment system (some of you may be familiar).  Long story short - in under six years, I obtained my Bachelors (w/honors) and Masters at Ashford.  I have found my degrees to be very valuable in the civilian sector and I would recommend Ashford to anyone that is serious about obtaining a quality education.<//Review>

<review>I am in a Physician Assistant program all because i received a degree from Ashford and it was one of the hardest things I have ever done in my life. The  work was challenging once I studied my concentration and I had to prove I understood the work by writing weekly multi-page reports. The while time I attended I wished I had attended a brick and mortar school because you can get away with doing minimal work and using relationships with teachers to receive good grades. I recommend going to book and mortar school if you do not want to spend the next 4 years working your butt off, I mean , I am in a medical program in Grad school and it is easier than doing online work. People, you will get out what you put in and if you are not at a university level educationally before you start your program, do not blame the school for your failure, work harder.
At the very least, Ashford prepared me to attend Graduate school.

I am a recent graduate of Ashford and I have nothing but good things to say about this school.  It is perfect for busy individuals that are serious about their education.  By following simple written instructions, taking weekly tests, and writing a final paper in each class I was able to finish in 2 years.

The five week class schedule means that you don't have to worry about someone wasting your time.  Everything is laid out in such a way that if you can follow written instruction you can pass each and every class with flying colors.

I plan to continue with Ashford to complete my MBA in the Fall and highly reccommend Ashford to anyone that is looking to further there education.<//Review>

< text>
I started school here in September (2015). At first I was kind of skeptical because of reviews I saw on their facebook page. Some people had some really harsh complaints, but I continued to look into. An enrollment advisor got in contact with me - she didn't pressure me, and I didn't get a thousand calls from them every day. In the end, she got me enrolled and transferred over financial aid that I was going to use at another on-campus University despite starting so late. I took my introductory course and am now on my third class. The staff is very patient and helpful and the time is very flexible (most assignments are due Thursday and Monday) so it gives me plenty of time to study and work while maintaining my every day life. It gets frustrating sometimes because some students in class don't act like they are very interested, or don't do their work properly for us to respond, but the ones who do take it seriously definitely make the process worthwhile! I'm actually excited about attending school here. Shout out to my advisor D. Mead for believing in me.</text>

< Text>
I graduated from Ashford with a bachelors - I double majored in Psychology & Health Care Administration.  I had an exceptional experience with this school, advisors, and all teachers.  This is an independent program so you get out what you put in.  I read all the negative reviews that people are writing and it sounds like they're blaming Ashford for their laziness or inability to hack it.  In response to the people saying that Ashford makes you take courses that have nothing to do with your degree - -  If you enroll in a four year degree program you are going to take classes that are general education courses - just like any other college.  At any college you do not take degree specific courses until your Junior and Senior year just like at Ashford.  Apparently these folks do not know how college courses work.  This is not a vocational school folks.  If you can read, absorb information, and write you should have no problem what so ever passing your courses.  I graduated with a 3.8 GPA.  In response to all the reviews saying this school is a scam - This is an online school and yes it is a little more expensive than going to a local school, but no one is making you go there.  At Ashford, along with all other colleges, there is a time frame for when you have to drop a class.  Depending on how long you wait determines how much of your money you get back.  This is standard in college courses.   In response to all the reviews that claim that no one would contact them after enrollment was completed - -I have never had a problem getting in touch with anyone - advisors, financial aid department, teachers, or anyone in the registrar's office.  You can contact vie phone, email, or through the student portal.  I honestly find your claims a total lie and not in line with my experience at all.  All in all - this was a perfect fit for me and my situation at the time.  I had small children at home and it worked perfectly.  Not everyone is cut out for online school - it requires a lot of discipline and motivation.< /Text>

A college is either accredited or its not, there is no such thing as "more accredited".
I personally have had an excellent experience with the University and have been in classes on and off for about 2 years. The OFF is my own doing, not theirs. Understandably, I get new advisors each time I enroll, for the most part, but they have been very attentive and get me what I need to get going again really quickly with no delays. For those who have issues with financial aid and "being told Im eligible and not getting my money", well its pretty cut and dry, you may be eligible for financial aid on the FAFSA, but if you are failing and dropping your classes, you will OWE the school money, and likely have a Pell Grant overpayment and owe the Dept of Ed. So, how about be prepared for school so you can pass your classes? That would solve the problems. Thats your fault not the schools.
Perfectly great school for those willing to work hard to get your work in. Its not for those who need a lot of structure, be independent before enrolling and you will be fine.</Review>< Pictures>

<name>Moon5niper<//name>< Review>
I've taken 4 classes at Ashford, 4.00 GPA. I'll be blunt, at least half of the people in every class haven't completed the course work properly or on time. People are not capable of following simple directions, so I have to question whether many of these negative reviews are simply due to user error... If you do not apply yourself you can fail, just like anything else in life. The only knock I have against Ashford is for all of the mismanagement involved with shutting down their Iowa campus, which has lead to negative press. I am active duty AF, so all of my costs are 100% covered, and cannot comment on FA issues.

EDIT: Updating review to say I graduated May 2018 with a 4.0, Summa Cum Laude. I still stand by my original review. The school is relatively easy and fair, AS LONG AS YOU DO WHAT YOU'RE SUPPOSED TO DO. You still have to complete all of the work, like actually write some 10 page papers, but you're not going to be nitpicked down for grades if you hit on all of the points you were required to talk about. That's how it's easy IMO.</Review>

103002177925941013525</user_id>
<Name>Bruce Kennedy</Name>< time>
1374726071928</time>
<rate>4</rate>< Text>
I am going to be as honest as possible with my review, and be willing to expose the rough edges, as well as the good points.
I am giving Ashford University 4 stars out of 5.  I have been a student now for well over a year.  Ashford University Online enrolls you in courses on a sequential basis.  Five weeks per course.  On to the next.  In most courses the reading is pretty challenging, and there are outside links provided for further study.  If you like to write, Ashford is for you.  Each week 2 discussion posts are due.  Each discussion is at minimum 250 words and must be supported by APA citation.  One posts his/her posts and responds to at least 2 other classmates.  Mid course (generally) a small 3-5 page research paper is due.  And on week 5 usually a final 8-12 page paper is due.  One must of course find scholarly sources and use APA citation style.
Bottom line...Ashford is no pushover!  The work is challenging, and if you want to maintain good grades you have to study and do a lot of writing.  But you can gain a degree in an online environment in a flexible enough schedule to work around a full time job.

Ok, Ashford had some accreditation troubles, granted.  But they have turned their whole philosophy as an institution around with a new president, and a leaner workforce, and just recently was praised by their new accrediting body the WASC (Western Association of Schools and Colleges) for having made many fundamental changes that have transformed Ashford as a learning institution.  Bottom line, they just bit off a bit more than they could chew in the beginning, had offices in the west and the school in Iowa, and grew bigger than their infrastructure could handle in the beginning.  (Hence all the negative reviews you may see here.)

Bottom line...again...the school has changed to be a much better school, and for me they are the only 4 year online institution that offers a degree program in teaching English to English Language Learners.

That is my dream...to teach kids English.  What is your dream?  Chances are you could find it at Ashford!< /Text>

<time>1387606798622</time><pics>None< /pics>< review>
First of all, I notice the only reviews "Yelp" recommends are the positive reviews. This public should see all of the reviews without navigating the maze of pages here to find them.

I often stay away from reviews because all to often we see a timed emotion, which doesn't describe the entire experience from a student while at this institution. I have attended two online universities and lack just a few classes from obtaining my BA. You may find grammatical errors in this post, but it does not take away from the truth it covers about Ashford.

Let‚Äôs start with the University of Phoenix, since that is where I cam from with my Associate‚Äôs. The instructors and staff were a lot more in-tune with the student. My only complaint was ‚Äúgroup projects‚Äù in the Bachelor‚Äôs level courses. This review isn‚Äôt about UOP, so I won‚Äôt go into detail, but the staff there seemed to care about the student, probably because classes were almost $2,000 a piece.

On to Ashford University: Jeffrey Woods was my admissions counselor, and as always, he was fantastic. This is a common theme among admissions counselors because they are the bread and butter of the company. He stuck with me for the first three classes. I couldn‚Äôt ask for anything better, so I was hooked.

I was moved to Chad Small after this‚Ä¶ and this is where it began. I required a receipt (Univ of Phoenix offered this on their site as self-service) for each paid class for tuition reimbursement purposes through my employer. The system is set up to auto-email these, so they tell me, but it never worked correctly. When I requested any items from Chad, he would take in excess of 2 weeks to respond, or many times he would simply not respond at all. I started attaching delivery notifications to each email, so then I received the response that my emails were deleted without being read; therefore I never received a response. I asked Chad over and over to improve his response time, left voicemails with this information, and asked to speak to his supervisor. I never received any of the requested items. I requested a new counselor, so I was moved to Elana Perry‚Ä¶ which would turn out to be worse than Chad.

I only had to contact Elana a handful of times during my 7-8 months with her, but ant hills turned into mountains when I requested anything. She was beyond rude, even telling me at one point that this is my education and my responsibility, not hers to deal with. She made me aware I was on her timeline, when I simply asked for her to follow-up with me before 4 days had passed with no response. She was beyond facetious and made no attempt to apologize or help me, the student.
I asked for yet another counselor, and this was made it clear in the beginning that she would respond to me when she could, which is usually 48-72 hours. Her name is Aimee Downes; in which business environment is it acceptable to write to the company in which you are a paying customer, with an issue, only to be put on hold for more than 3 days?

Overall, the university does not care about the students, do not work for you but against you, and is the biggest joke for a business that I have ever encountered. We get better service at Taco Bell! The counselors, after your admissions timeframe ends, are rude, non-responsive, and their managers are no different.

Sadly I am so close to finishing that I, like others, have trapped myself in their circle of chaos. Why switch now, only to do more paperwork, attend more entry classes, and risk my classes not transferring. I wish I would have done this different, but I will continue to swap counselors until they treat me like the customer I am, which is a high paying customer.< /review>

< text>
I had a great experience at the Ben Bridge Jeweler at the Tyler Galleria. Roy‚ÄôAlle and the team at this location (including Wany and Dee) provided me incredible support and service...highly professional and with a very customer friendly focus.

In short - I had been searching for a Rolex Stainless Steel Sport model for many months. I went to multiple AD‚Äôs and had no success in finding one - all were out of stock for these Rolex sport models. Granted I know these are highly constrained and in fact I had resigned to the fact that it may be impossible to get one for maybe 1 - 2 years. However, to my pleasant surprise, I got a call from Roy‚ÄôAlle that they had just got one in stock and it was mine for the purchase if I wanted it.

Of course I quickly jumped on it and purchased the watch. When I went in to pick it up was when I was able to experience their top tier and high quality of service and attention to me as a valued customer. After sizing the watch there were some issues getting the links loose to remove two of them. Being a Rolex, these link screws don‚Äôt just unscrew...they require a special machine to loosen them. After a few tries w/o any success they recommended that they send it to one of their locations with an experienced watch maker and that I come back in a few days to pick it up once the bracelet is properly adjusted. This wasn‚Äôt ideal since it was some distance for me to get there, but taking the watch with the two links still on the bracelet would surely result in me trying to do this myself at home, which would most likely not have a good outcome for the watch.

I think they could sense, that although I understood this, I was a bit bummed. So they each took another try and finally, Wany was able to get it and I was able to leave with my new watch that same day. They didn‚Äôt have to go to the extra effort, but they really wanted to help and see me leave with the watch that day...and this was very appreciated on my end.

I would highly recommend This Ben Bridges store. These guys are awesome!!! I didn‚Äôt even have to buy a bunch of stuff to get some Rolex priority, which is often the case at many AD‚Äôs...this was my first purchase here and it was a Rolex sport model. Certainly, I‚Äôll be a loyal customer going forward.< /text>

<Text>GO HERE. For everything!!!

Me and my fianc√© came here to find our ring. We were particularly interested in this jeweler because of their bridal deal of 12 months interest free payments. As we arrived we were greeted by Karla Rivas. I had looked on their website before coming in so that I had an idea of what I wanted, because they have a huge variety! I found a picture online of a ring with leaf-like designs, and I showed Karla the picture. Although they did not have the exact ring I showed, she brought two rings with a very similar, and almost more elegant leaf-like design along the sides. She showed me one option, which was cheaper, and was exactly what I was looking for. She also showed me a more expensive ring, that came with a wedding band as it is difficult to find a wedding band to go with a leaf designed ring. But because me and my fianc√© are not planning on getting married for a few more years and we‚Äôre on a budget, we stuck with the cheaper ring. What I loved about Karla is she did not push the more expensive ring to us. She simply showed us the pros and cons, and when we made our decision she respected it. She gave me her cell number so that we could be in contact through the whole process. My mother gave me a diamond to use as the center piece, which was 3/4 karat, but the ring we chose was made for a 1/2 karat. Karla walked us through all our options to customize the ring. Again, she explained to us a cheaper option, and a more expensive, more custom option. Due to the fact that I did not really want to change anything about the ring, we went with the cheaper option which was to simply get larger prongs. Karla explained everything step by step, and made sure our payment was low enough for us.

I‚Äôm writing this review as I‚Äôm NOT happy with the service I received by the Internet Sales Director, Bruce. <Date>1494465560489</Date><rating>1< /rating>< review>
The worst customer service I have had anywhere.  I would give them no stars if there was an option to do so. The service department here is not competent to work on non-honda cars.  The service manager there is very rude and lacks any and all manners how to treat a customer.

I called them on Tuesday May 9th 2017 to get a price quote for an oil change.  The person said he would call me back.  He left a message with a price of around $75. So I went to them that afternoon but they were busy so I scheduled one for the next morning. While I was there he gave me a quote for $58.  I signed the paperwork and he said they would call me once it was done.  I also asked them to check the air filter as well.  As more time elapsed and I had not heard from them, I called them back that afternoon to see what the status was.  He said they had not started yet as they were trying to get a hold of me on the phone.  I never received any calls from them BTW.  He said they had not started because there was a price discrepancy and the total now would be $71.99.  I agreed to the change.

An hour later he called me to say they were done.  I asked him again if they reset the service interval notice on the car and he said they did.  After paying the cashier and started my car, I noticed that the service interval was still on.  I asked them to reset it and they said they already had.  After going back and forth with another service rep, who gave me many bogus reasons about how that was normal, I asked to speak with a manager. As they realized that they could not do this service, they asked me to take my car to an audi dealer.  I told them this was going to cost me additional and wondered why they did not tell me this in the first place and that the dealership was not equipped with tools to work on an audi.  The manager initially told the rep to give me partial credit and then rudely changed his mind. He said I was being rude to the people there, just because I was trying to explain that what they were saying was incorrect and that the service interval warning should be reset after an oil change. He later told the rep " You know what, don't even give him any credit. Just give him his keys and get him OUT of here!"

When I asked the manager for his business card, he said NO! He said to call the owner of the dealership if I wanted to talk to someone higher in rank than him.

Notes to the dealership:
If you are going to work on cars that have an onboard computer, then please get a VAGCOM diagnostic tool so you can take care of simple resets like the one my car needed. It is fairly inexpensive.

If you are incapable of working on cars other than Honda, then be upfront about it.

And if you are going to be rude to customers who spend their money at your establishment, don't take their business and chase them out of there unsatisfied.

Notes to the service manager:
You are a service industry. And these days, a bad review will cost your business money when you don't treat your customers right.

Also, check the attached photo of your service receipt. Notice the quote  "WE WANT YOU COMPLETELY SATISFIED" in bold.

Well Sir, I am NOT SATISFIED!<//review>

< Review>
I bought my 2018 Honda Odyssey in June of 2017 their customer service is incredible!!! They were very courteous and helpful, the night we bought my car they stayed way past closing time to finish the deal and show me all the different features in the car patiently. When we had an issue with the car, they took me right away and arranged for a rental fully paid on the spot. The service manager was very courteous and professional, he took care of our concerns and even threw in a set of Honda leather mats for the car. They gave us an amazing discount when the car had just been released and none of the other dealers would, we called dealers in Las Vegas (where I got my last Odyssey) and Huntington Beach, they were the most competitive. In addition to all that, they worked hard to find and get me the color and trim that I had requested, I got it in a week( which is very fast considering the car had just been released and the dealers were still getting them in).
